## Javascript Fundamentals

How do you check if an element exists in an array? Of course you can iterate over it, but an easier solution is with a conditional. I first saw this at [bennadel.com](http://www.bennadel.com/blog/177-Javascript-Short-Hand-IF-Within-Object-Notation.htm)


\begin{codeblock}
// Create an array of friends.
var arrFriends = new Array("Molly", "Sarah", "Dave", "Luke");

// Get the day of the week.
var intDayOfWeek = 6 //:(new Date()).getDay();
// Figure out which friend to call based on
// the given day of the week. Call Luke on saturday.
// For every other day, call Molly (my girlfriend).
var strFriendToCall = arrFriends[(intDayOfWeek == 6) ? 3 : intDayOfWeek];

log(strFriendToCall);

var i = 2;
(i > 2) ? log('ok') : log('notok');
\end{codeblock}

Nothing earth shuttering, but neat. Just a reminder about the ternary conditional statement:

<pre><code>
   conditionExpr ? thenExpr : elseExpr; 
</code></pre>

